A Message
From the Dean

By Dr. G. R. Fitterer

Whether we like it or not, we American engineers have
been challenged by the Russians and we must accept the
challenge with vigor. In either a “hot” or “cold” war, a
large portion of the responsibility for winning the contest
will be ours. We cannot fail.

It did not take much imagination on the part of the
Russians following our victories in World War I and II to
conclude that we in America had something unique which
twice stopped the German war machine. America entered
both wars late and, at times, when all of Europe, including
Russia, had their backs to the wall, and when the Germans
had. nearly attained a total victory.

The Russian leaders know that they could not have ac-
complished their victories in the latter part of World War
II without our help. We all but smothered them with a
deluge of guns, ammunition, planes, tanks, and many other
necessities of war, including food, at a time while we were
stimultaneously winning another war in the Pacific without
their help.

Although in recent years America has become the science
center of the world, this was not true during these two wars.
Instead, it was Germany which was considered the mecca
of science. How then were we able to win these most techno-
logic of all wars? It was undoubtedly through our type of
engineering education which has been unique in this world

JANUARY I96!

G. R. Fitterer

—until now. And now, the Russians have copied many of
the good points of our curricula and some of Germany’s,
and are turning out 110,000 engineers per year to our 35,000.

Russia’s one goal is world domination. With all of these
engineers they have enough to develop the material of a
“hot” war and at the same time many engineers can be
sent to foreign lands to take part in technical assistant pro-
grams of the “cold” war.

Brazil, which is lar-ger than the United States and has
about one—third the population, is probably the most rapidly
growing nation in the world. Brazilian colleges graduate
only about 4-00 engineers per year, whereas on our scale
they should be graduating at least 11,000 compared to our
needs and 27,000 compared to the Russians.

The Brazilians must look elsewhere for their engineers,
and since we are hardly graduating enough to meet our
own needs, they are turning to Russia for this help. It is
the only other country producing engineers with any simi-
larity to ours.

Meanwhile, our emphasis through government assistance
in this country has turned to the development of scientists
and not engineers. For these reasons every engineer in this
country will be greatly needed and he must extend his
thinking to include world problems. The answers to a great
majority of these are not political.

