BY HOWARD KANESS

A nuclear steam electric generating station is being
built on the Hudson River 24 miles north of New York
City. One of the problems in building this station is to
make the cost of the energy produced from the initial
reactor as low and as nearly competitive as possible
with conventional steam generation costs. Since present
limitations of pressurized water reactors result in saturated
steam of relatively low pressure and temperature as com-
pared to modern steam plants, an investigation of the
economics of superheating the steam generated by the
reactor before using it in the turbo-generator was made.
The cost, capacity, and plant heat rate were calculated
for a plant using the saturated steam produced by the
reactor to run the turbine, and for an alternate plant in

 

