which the steam from the reactor would be channeled
through separate oil-fired superheaters. The economics of
superheating the reactor steam to temperatures of 860F,
1000F, and 1050F were studied. The most satisfactory
care was at 1000F. The steam pressure at the throttle was
reduced from 405 psig at the boiler to 355 psig because of
the pressure drop in the superheater and piping.

The station will have an electric capability of 275
Megawatts; 163 MW from the reactor and 112 MW from
two oil-fired superheaters. The reactor is a pressurized
water, internal thorium converter. It will be the first unit
to make use of thorium as the fertile material to supple-
ment the base fuel, enriched U-235. The heat capability
of the reactor portion of the station will be 585 MW.

The addition of superheat to the cycle results in an
increase in capacity from 163,0.00 KW to 275,000 KW and
a reduction in cost from $524 per KW for a plant using
only nuclear fuel to an average cost of $379 per KW
for the combination of nuclear boiler and oil-fired super-
heaters. The use of superheat will also reduce the main-
tenance costs on the turbine as compared to a unit operat-
ing on wet steam.

The general layout of the station follows the general
arrangement used in conventional steam plants except the

nuclear reactor replaces the conventional boiler.

The station’s heat balance is as follows: To develop
an electrical output of 275MW, 2,200,000 pounds of steam
per hour generated in the boilers at 405 psig and heated to
1000F in two half-size superheaters will be introduced into
the turbine generator at 355 psig, and will be exhausted
to the condenser.

Condensate will be returned to the boilers after being
heated in a string of three closed heaters, an economizer,
and a high pressure deaerator. The condensate flowing
through the three closed heaters and the deaerator is heated
by bleed steam from the turbines and by an economizer
between the superheaters and the stack. From the deaerator,
the boiler feed pumps will return the condensate to the
boilers of the nuclear steam generator.

The heat rate of the steam cycle, exclusive of reactor
efficiency, is 10,700 Btu per KWH.

The nuclear steam generator consists of (1) the
reactor and its heat transfer system containing valves,
piping, pumps, boilers, and pressurizer; (2) reactor safety
and control systems; (3) safety containment vessel and
auxiliary equipment; (4) coolant treatment and makeup
systems; and (5) waste disposal facilities for collection, stor-
age and disposal of solid, liquid and gaseous wastes.

The reactor core is an internal thorium converter. The
reactor utilizes enriched uranium as the base fuel in the
form of uranium oxide, and thorium oxide as the fertile
material. The two materials are mixed and put in rod
type fuel elements.

Thorium was chosen as the fertile material on the
basis of (1) its ability to supplement the base fuel by the
production of fissionable U-233, (2) its radiation stability,
(3) its high resistance to corrosion in high temperature
water, and (4) its compatibility with uranium oxide and
stainless steel.

The first core, composed of 120 fuel elements, will have

