BY ROY MARANGONI

Courier’s ornamental appearance misrepresents its work-
horse capabilities; its surface covered by thousands of bluish,
highly reflective solar cells has outwardly little in common
with the typical olive drab military communications equip-
ment. Only the antennas, protruding from a white band
around its middle, give it a functional look.

Different from its recent predecessors, the Department
of Defense’s Courier is not intended for navigation purposes
or scientific measurements, nor is it on a reconnaissance
patrol in space. It is out in space expressly to test its ability
to relay messages for communications between ground sta-
tions. Its capacity is estimated to be equivalent to 3,400,000
words a day or approximately enough words to fill 465 solid
pages of newspaper information without ads or pictures in
the standard eight-column size newspaper page.

Courier’s successful operation now opens the door to
untold future developments in civilian world communica-
tions. Its success foretells highly reliable transoceanic deliv-
ery of messages by means of satellites. These messages for-
merly were interrupted by atmospheric disturbances to radio
circuits or they suffer-ed costly delays in underwater cable
movement. While the satellite is designed for delayed
delivery of messages, comparable to a land-line telegraph or
teletype system, provision has been built into the Courier
enabling instantaneous relay of messages between two
ground stations which can see the satellite simultaneously.

The precision of control over the satelli~te’s equipment
was made possible by its built-in digital logic system, called
the command decoder. Designed to use logic modules, the
command decoder checks all incoming signals and com-
mands with regard to procedural correctness, signal strength
adequacy, and compatability with the sa,tellite’s function-
ing at that instant. It routes any acceptable command to
the appropriate equipment and then initiates a coded ac-
knowledgement signal which is transmitted back to the

ground station.

As the satellite orbits the earth it passes over a ground
station in a predictable manner. During a pass, the following
typical sequence of events takes place: the horizontal sector
from which the satellite Miss is expected is illuminated by
the ground station antenna, operating at VHF. As the low

11

powered acquisition beacon in the satellite appears in the
antenna field, a coded command is initiated by the ground
stations to switch the satellite from a “stand by” to an “ac-
tive” mode of operation. This command activates a VHF
satellite transmitter, which will begin to radiate after a
short warm up period. The satellite VHF acquisition trans-
mitter is switched off and the high powered satellite VHF
telemetry transmitter begins to transmit telemetry data to
the ground station. After the ground station receives ac-
knowledgment of its first command, the ground antenna
goes into a “scan” mode at microwave frequency. When
the satellite microwave signal appears in the beam of the
ground antenna, the ground station automatically begins
to track the satellite.

Commands to the space station, after the command
to activate, are made through the microwave link. Each
command is preceded by a code which is changed in accord-
ance with a predetermined method of operation. In event
of fading or other loss of signal, the satellite automatically
returns to the acquisition mode and the process may then
be repeated. Data relay or exchange is accomplished during
the 10 to 15 minute period in which the satellite is within
range of the ground station. The satellite is then commanded
to return from “active” to “stand by” condition.

The satellite is powered by the sun’s rays. In outer
space the sun is not a diffused shower of rays as on the
earth. Rather, it is a tiny line of energy striking only
one side of the satellite at a time. Accordingly, a compli-
cated solar outer shell consisting of some 20,000 individual
cells wired together, provides an unprecedented 62 watts of
power. This is equivalent to the amount of power necessary
to illuminate a living room lamp bulb twenty-four hours a
day.

