the solar arrays can supply. The batteries also provide a
means whereby the satellite can operate when it is in the
earth’s shadow.

The outer shell of the satellite functions as a support
for the cell arrays and as a shield for heat control and
meteorite erosion. The design consists of two lightweight
hemispheres joined ‘together at the inner structure equa-
torial band with detachable fasteners to establish a form
which is approximately spherical in shape. Major access to
the inner structure and its equipment is obtained by sep-
arating the hemispheres. The hemispheres are fabricated
from a plastic honey-comb sandwich between two thin skins
of fiberglass. In addition to providing adequate strength,
the thickness of the honey-comb cellular results in an ex-
tremely rigid surface for mounting the solar cells. The
honey-comb cells are permeable to the outside of the satel-
lite to eliminate the possibility of air diffusion to the inside.
In addition to this permeability, major venting is provided
through the entire outer shell.

The inner structure of the satellite is made in the form
of welded aluminum platforms which support the various
items of equipment in the payload. The payload is almost
equally divided into message handling equipment and spare
equipment. The spare parts in most cases are to be switched
into the system by ground command if failures occur. There-

