to the coal below. This article will describe the methods and
machinery now commonly used in strip mining in northwest-
ern Pennsylvania. .

One of the major methods of removing the overburden
is to use giant “drag-lines.” These are so called because the
digging operation consists of dragging a bucket. These drag-
lines come in various sizes but are usually very large with
high capacity buckets. One thing all drag-lines have is
mobility. Some are mounted on caterpillar-like treads while
others use a very unusual “walking” technique.

The author visited two different drag-line machines in
collecting material for the article. The first machine was a
diesel-powered 1954 Paige Drag-Line owned by the Chutz
Brothers and operating outside of Harrisville, Pennsylvania.
This particular machine has two levels in the main cab. It
is equipped with a 135 ft. long boom and a 13 cubic yd.
capacity bucket.

The main power for the hoisting, dragging, and walking
is supplied by an approximately 800 HP, V-6 Diesel engine.
It operates at only 450 rpm with a 16 in. stroke and 121/2 in.
diameter pistons. One unusual feature of this engine is that
it lays on its side.

There is a smaller 350 HP, 3 cylinder engine on the sec-
ond level and it drives an electric generator. This generator
supplies power for the two swing motors, lights, and an air
compressor. The air compressor is used to supply air to the
electrically-valved air controls of the drag—line and the
swing motors are used to turn the cab and boom to either
side. The steel rope cable, used to drag the bucket, is 21/3
in. diameter and the lift cable is 17/8 in. The drag and lift
motions are braked through mechanical friction brakes and
they are started through mechanical clutches.

