DRILLING RIGS such as this drill continuously so that blast-
ing can be used to loosen the earth.

Everything on the drilling rig is hydraulically powered.
The drill stem is lifted and driven down by hydraulic mo-
tors. Using hydraulic power for everything has resulted in
much less breakage through smoother power transmission to
the drill bit, and reduced shock effects.

After the holes are drilled, an explosive such as am-
monium nitrate (fertilizer) is tamped in the holes and
detonated. The blast breaks up the rock and soil and allows
the drag-line to operate much more efficiently.

The drag-lines remove the loose soil and work down
to the coal seam. Then the last remaining dirt on the seam
is carefully removed by highlifts or bulldozers. When all the
dirt is removed, power shovels are brought up to the edge
of the coal seam and begin to load the coal into trucks
brought down into the pit. The power shovel pictured is a
diesel-powered 1% yd. capacity machine. While the pic-
tured trucks are dual-axle 15 ton capacity, it only takes 6
or 7 shovel fulls to load each truck.

The coal is carried from the pits by these trucks. Next
stop for the coal is the tipple. Here the coal is sorted and
rocks picked from it. Then the coal is put into railroad cars
to be taken to buyers.‘

This is the way coal is usually strip mined in north-
western Pennsylvania. Coal mining is a large and extensive
industry employing a large labor force of highly skilled men
to operate the machinery. The heavy equipment used is
among the largest and most expensive built in America.
Strip mining is rapidly evolving into a highly efficient and
scientific industry using the latest possible methods for the
lowest possible costs. With new uses for coal being discovered,
coal mining may again become a major industry in the tri-
state area of Pennsylvania, Ohio, and West Virginia.

