errors on our streets and highways, any of us can be in-
volved in a serious accident caused by someone else’s careless
driving.

The way motorists are knocked about in accidents is a
cause of grave concern to safety and traffic experts as well
as automotive engineers. Motor companies, universities, the
Air Force and leading organizations concerned with safety
have done a great amount of research and have suggested
quite a few interior refinements. As a result of these sug-
gestions the automotive industry has introduced padded
dashboards and visors, head rest, recessed steering wheel,
and in particular, safety belts in the American passenger
car. A close look at all of these reveals that each merits
consideration.

Often upon collision the passengers are thrown for-
ward. By padding the dashboard and sun visors, the chance
of a severe injury in these areas is lessened. But the area
between these two, the windshield, which is usually the
obstacle that is struck, cannot be padded and offers no
protection. Therefore, although the use of padding on the
dashboard and sun visors is useful, it alone is of little use.

Frequently after impact the occupant will fall back
against the seat. The back rest is only shoulder high and the
force of the fall will very often snap the occupant’s neck
since there is nothing to restrain the motion of his head at
the same time his body is being restrained. Increasing the
height of the back rest would solve this but it is not practical
since it would obstruct the rear view of the occupants. This
can be solved by putting a head rest where the occupant
usually sits which would not decrease his rear view. How-
ever, there is no guarantee that when he leaves his seat he
will come back in the same place. Therefore, the head rest

SKYSCRAPER ENGINEER

is useful, but by itself useless.
The recessed steering wheel is an example of a device

which is useful by itself. It is now standard equipment on
all modern automobiles and has greatly reduced a major
cause of injury and death. The top of the steering post on
older cars is in the same plane as the wheel, whereas when
the driver is thrown forward his chest is crushed against
the immovable post. With the post recessed below the plane
of the wheel, the driver’s forward motion is retarded by the
wheel and not the post. Even if the wheel should break under
impact it will decrease the acceleration force of the driver.
The importance of this device is perhaps shown in the fact
that it is the only recent innovation to be used by the auto-
motive industry as standard and not as optional equipment.

Injuries tend to be worse when a person is thrown from
the car; new safety door latches help restrain him. Re-
search crash studies, using actual vehicles, demonstrated
that doors frequently opened, even during relatively low-
speed collisions and permitted the occupants to be ejected
from the car. Investigation showed that the door latching
elements slipped out of engagement because of the dif-
ferential movement between the door and body which oc-
cured during an Impact. Various latch designs were

