In the Spring of 1959 a class in Industry 14-3—Human
Relations, decided to make a small pilot study in the field
of job selection by graduating Seniors. The purpose of this
study was to evaluate the reaction of college graduates to
various factors connected with their first jobs following
graduation.

Heavy reliance was placed on a study done by Opinion
Research which sought to determine the most important
factors which influence the college senior in the choice of
his first job. Many surveys have been made to determine
what factors are regarded as most important. In general,
they have come up with about the same list of factors.

However, a cursory search of the literature of college
placement has not revealed any study determining how the
college graduate felt about these factors at least one year
after beginning work on his first job.

For example, if a college graduate felt that “chance for
advancement” should be a very important factor in his job
choice, did he feel that he had made a wise choice one year
later in so far as chance for advancement was concerned?
In a like manner, other factors that theoretically determined
the graduates choice of a job were included in a question-
naire sent to a number of college graduates.

